31","1220":"1220","about 1255":"okolo 1255","1195":"1195","about 1220":"okolo 1220","1290":"1290","Devon, England":"Devon, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1220–":"omkring 1220–Afdød","1220–Male":"1220–Afdød","1222–Female":"1222–Afdød","1255–1331":"1255–1331","1190–Male":"1190–Afdød","1195–Female":"1195–Afdød","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1255":"1255","1222":"1222","1331":"1331","1220":"1220","about 1255":"omkring 1255","1195":"1195","about 1220":"omkring 1220","1290":"1290","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"nl":{"about 1220–":"circa 1220–Overleden","1220–Male":"1220–Overleden","1222–Female":"1222–Overleden","1255–1331":"1255–1331","1190–Male":"1190–Overleden","1195–Female":"1195–Overleden","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1255":"1255","1222":"1222","1331":"1331","1220":"1220","about 1255":"circa 1255","1195":"1195","about 1220":"circa 1220","1290":"1290","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"about 1220–":"about 1220–Deceased","1220–Male":"1220–Deceased","1222–Female":"1222–Deceased","1255–1331":"1255–1331","1190–Male":"1190–Deceased","1195–Female":"1195–Deceased","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1255":"1255","1222":"1222","1331":"1331","1220":"1220","about 1255":"about 1255","1195":"1195","about 1220":"about 1220","1290":"1290","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Halton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): habitational name from any of several places called Halton in Cheshire, Lancashire, Yorkshire, Northumberland, Lincolnshire, Shropshire and Buckinghamshire. Halton is usually from Old English <i>h(e)alh</i> ‘nook, hollow’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. Halton in Cheshire, however, is possibly named from an Old English <i>hāthel</i> ‘heathery place’ + <i>tūn</i>, and Halton in Northumberland from an Old English <i>hāw</i> ‘look out’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’ + <i>tūn</i>.","Irish: variant of   Holton  .","History: Most English bearers of this name trace their descent from William de Halton, who was living at Halton, Lancashire, in 1346."],"variants":[{"name":"Holton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Holton, such as those in Oxfordshire, Suffolk, Dorset, and Somerset. The Oxfordshire and Somerset placenames derive from Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, while the Suffolk placename comes from the Old English personal name <i>Hōla</i> + <i>tūn</i>. The Dorset placename derives from Old English <i>hol</i> ‘hole, hollow’ or <i>holt</i> ‘wood, grove, thicket’ + <i>tūn</i>.","Irish: altered form of <b>O'Haltahan</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hUltacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ultachán</i>’, a diminutive of <i>Ultach</i> ‘Ulsterman’. This is a rare Fermanagh surname, sometimes Anglicized as   Nolan  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":4,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":39,"year